#1.Relation between Gender and Spending Score

# Analyzing the relationship between Gender and Spending Score
# Initializing variables to calculate male and female spending scores to Caluclate male and female spending scores
spending_score_male = 0
spending_score_female = 0
# Looping through the DataFrame to calculate spending scores based on gender
for i in range(len(d_f)):
    if d_f['Gender'][i] == 0:
        spending_score_male += d_f['Spending_score'][i]
    if d_f['Gender'][i] == 1:
        spending_score_female += d_f['Spending_score'][i]
        
# Displaying the calculated spending scores for males and females        
print("Males Spending Score: ",spending_score_male)
print("Females Spending Score: ",spending_score_female)

Males Spending Score:  4269
Females Spending Score:  5771

#Gender & Total Spending Score


# Creating a list of total spending scores for females and males
list_genders_spending_score = [int(spending_score_female),\
                               int(spending_score_male)]
# Converting the list to a Pandas Series
series_genders_spending_score = pd.Series(\
                            data = list_genders_spending_score)
# Creating a subplot and plotting a bar chart for Gender & Total Spending Score
plt.subplot(3,3,3)
plots = sns.barplot(x=['Female','Male'], \
        y=series_genders_spending_score, palette=['yellow','purple'])
# Annotating the bar chart with total spending scores
for bar in plots.patches:
    plots.annotate(format(bar.get_height(), '.0f'),\
        (bar.get_x() + bar.get_width() / 2, bar.get_height()),\
        ha='center', va='center',size=13, xytext=(0, 8),\
                   textcoords='offset points',color='red')

plt.grid(False)
plt.title("Gender & Total Spending Score\n", color="red", size='22')

# Annotating the bar chart with mean spending scores

    plots.annotate(format(bar.get_height(), '.0f'),\
        (bar.get_x() + bar.get_width() / 2,bar.get_height()),\

In [25]:
#BUILDING THE MODEL
#1.Spending score vs Annual Income
#Step1: Finding no.of clusters by Elbow method

#Creating values for the elbow
X1 =d_f[['Spending_score','Annual_income']].values
inertia = []

# Looping through different cluster values to calculate the inertia (Within-Cluster-Sum-of-Squares)
for i in range(1,15):
    means_k = KMeans(n_clusters=i, random_state=0) # Inertia represents WCSS (Within-Cluster-Sum-of-Squares)
    means_k.fit(X1)
    inertia.append(means_k.inertia_)
In [26]:
#Plotting the elbow

# Creating a figure for the plot
plt.figure(1 , figsize = (10 ,4))
# Plotting the number of clusters vs. inertia
plt.plot(range (1,15) , inertia,'bo-')
# Adding labels to the axes
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters') , plt.ylabel('Inertia')
# Displaying the plot
plt.show()

OBSERVATIONS:

(Using matplotlib we have plotted the above graph) The elbow method plots the value of the cost function produced by different values of k. In this problem, we are using the inertia as cost function in order to identify the sum of squared distances of samples to the nearest cluster centre. By looking at the graph we can say number of clusters are equal to 5. Therefore we are selecting 5 as the number of clusters to divide our data.

#Step2:Clustering

# Initializing KMeans with the chosen number of clusters (5 in this case)
km1=KMeans(n_clusters=5)

# Fitting the input data to the KMeans model
km1.fit(X1)

# Predicting the labels of the input data points
y=km1.predict(X1)

# Adding a new column 'label' to the DataFrame to store cluster labels
d_f["label"] = y

# Agglomerative clustering with complete-linkage criterion

# Initializing AgglomerativeClustering with the chosen number of clusters (5 in this case) and 'complete' linkage

# Assigning cluster labels to the DataFrame using Agglomerative Clustering with complete linkage
